WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000
So Miss Tamer, we were talking about when you were out at Alcorn in the early 1940s.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Can you tell me what it was like?

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:24.000
The campus was the building. We didn't have that many buildings on the campus.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:33.000
They were far apart. I was out there about two months ago. It looked like a city beside what we had.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Were there most of the main gong? Were there mostly females on the campus?

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:45.000
The world was in hot, really going fast for the black community. There were a few millions on campus.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And you said you went to Alcorn for two years?

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Yes, and then I transferred to Tennessee and now.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
What made you transfer?

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:04.000
After my brothers had gone to Alcorn, they found out that, well, if we wanted to do graduate work, you would have to do make-up work coming out of Alcorn.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And I found that out when I got to Tennessee because the dean was at Tennessee. He used to work at Alcorn. He threw out all my education.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:23.000
He kept me there a quarter longer than I would have been there because I was at some school and I would have been out.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.000
I had to go back and pick up that education. He said that education I had at Alcorn was old as he was.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
But that wasn't my fault. Alcorn should have all fought better.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Could you tell the difference in the classes?

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Oh, yes. Oh, yes.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Sounds like you liked Tennessee.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Well, they were much harder.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Because really, we didn't have the foundation that we should have had.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Even though you actually probably had a better education coming into it than most African-Americans had opportunity for at the time.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
I don't know. These children came out to City School with so much violence and we were.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
You think that was a difference?

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:10.000
They had his first school, his law school. They were far more advanced than we were.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Do you think that was because they put more resources into it or they had teachers that were more education?

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:26.000
I think they had no money to do something with it. They probably had later books and we never saw a new book.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Never saw a new settle in Cyclopea.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So from what we were talking about earlier, it sounds like that most of the resources for the schools you went to came from the black community and that there wasn't much contribution from the government.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:51.000
I think they were supposed to have given us, but they took the, always took the best for our children and we got what left over.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
What did you do after you left Tennessee? And did you graduate with your...

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
I graduated in 1947. I got a bachelor degree in home in Kilimanjee.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
What did you do? I could find a job in Jasper County and I taught home to get to know me in Jasper County.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:16.000
I believed it was three years. Then I came to Jones County. If I'm Jones County, I came to Forest County.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I taught home to get to know me several years in Forest County.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
What made you move from one school to another?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Battle Sauron. You from then to pay.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
What were those schools like that you were teaching in?

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
There was just a step ahead of the high school I finished with.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:43.000
We didn't have the resources for the children. But we did the best we could as teachers.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
We had a lot of college graduates by the time I was teaching.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
They didn't have them when I was going to school.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
They might have had more and I can think they were one or two graduate from college.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Most of them were finished at those in normal schools.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
I know people could teach with a high school degree in those early years.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:09.000
If they could pass that test in the superintendent's office, which he couldn't pass.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So that was the white superintendent?

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
They couldn't help you with anything when you were on that.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
I know when I was making my first home and getting out with a reporter, I went on and asked him if he could have the forms.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
He said no. Look at what the other teachers used to teach you.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Like that.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Where would your report go to?

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
It would go to the county.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I think they would send it to the state. I don't know where it would go after then.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
But we had to make reports.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Was it related to the county extension?

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Yes.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
How did you meet Mr. Daymer?

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
They needed a home economic teacher now here.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:54.000
When they came up there and I was available, I was available because it paid more money.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So you were available because you wanted to be available?

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Well, the money would make you available.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So you came and you were teaching in Hattisburg in Fortes County?

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Teaching in Fortes County right out there.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
What Dennis went out there for the first time?

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
So you were right here in Kelly's cell.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Right in Kelly's cell.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Do you remember when you met Mr. Daymer for the first time?

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
I went to my house here and several more people came up there to be about the job.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And of course I was cooking down there.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And they didn't leave until 8.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
They stayed for dinner.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
You were going to get them out.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
And I don't know if they was even invited for dinner.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
But they said we were probably invited.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
They probably, but he didn't need to eat.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
I know that much.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Was it inevitable after that moment?

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.000
No.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
It was developed later on.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
So did you like teaching here in Kelly's cell?

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Yes.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I like teaching here.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
I talked to the integrated schools.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And after they integrated the school, they told the principal who they didn't have them

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
who to have, but they told them who not to have.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And my name was on that list.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So was that in 1970 or 1966?

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
I know that they integrated at different times.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:18.000
Now they integrated in?

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Was it with freedom of choice or was it after that?

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
It was with the full freedom of choice.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:31.000
I think consolidated all the black schools in Forest County into one school.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
And they were named at Earl Travegan.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And that's when they didn't rehire you?

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.000
That's when they didn't rehire me.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
They built a new school around there for all the black students in Forest County.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
The white school kept the schools where they were.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:54.000
The auditorium had to pass by them going to that school.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And that was probably in the late 50s or 60s?

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:02.000
I believe it was in the 50s, I believe it.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And so when they consolidated at Earl Travegan, you stopped teaching?

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
I stopped teaching in Forest County.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
I was the leader, the same year I believe it's consolidated.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
I was able to get a job in Paracabra.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Where is Paracabra? How far away is that?

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
30 miles, Rister.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
And were you still teaching home economic?

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
No. That is how I went up.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
By then I had gone to Elmerman.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.000
I had gone to Elmerman before I left Forest County.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
I went to the second era first in Elmerman.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Okay. Can you tell me about Mr. Damon?

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
What was he like?

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
If I've ever seen a Christian person he was one.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
He put Christianity into practice.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
He was really concerned about his fellowman.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.000
We had a comfortable living on the farm in the sawmill

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
and the grocery store on the plane of mail.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.000
At that time we had a very comfortable living.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.000
But he wanted to make things better for other people.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
When you married, did he own all this land

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
or was he working with other family members?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
He owned this right here.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Of course he had sisters in brother that own land.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
He was working some of that land.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Okay. So he worked his own land and their land?

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
Uh-huh. And some of that land.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.000
Before you had children who helped him work on the land?

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:39.000
He had hired help. He had hired help.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And of course he had tractors.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
I tractors and do farm old living in a horse.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
I mean we can't go to plow.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
He first started with a one road tractor

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
and then he moved to a two road tractor

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
and that was really good to do something.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And then he, as his boy's group,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Dennis was driving a tractor.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Dennis was driving a car and he was 12 years old.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So he's children are in the work early.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Betty was driving a car before she was 10.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
That was really good.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
All the incident that they burned out half Betty

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
was just 10 and a half.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
And when she was,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
I want to ask you about that,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
but I thought maybe I should ask you some other things.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
When she was driving a car at the age of 10 or that,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:27.000
around that,

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
would she do that just here around the place?

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Right, around the place.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
You know, you didn't know to get out on the road.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Maybe she'd go from the house or maybe up to an aunt's house on the road.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
But the traffic was not that like it is now.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
It wasn't as dangerous.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
They didn't have to have a driver license around here.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
Children on the farm learned to drive early.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Because all you need you to do is get off the gas

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
and let the truck roll.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
Then get on the brakes to stop the truck from rolling.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And when they keep on doing that,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
somebody just used to go and put it in the airfoam.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
But they learned to put it in that one cell.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
Early.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
Well, they had a lot of responsibility.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Yes. Everybody helped.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:14.000
So how many children did you all have?

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
Okay, let me tell you about it.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
We had six boys.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.000
Seven.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And as soon as they were old enough,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
they would all help on the farm.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Everybody had something to do.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Better to put you in.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
She worked all her life.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Even when we were playing cards,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Betty could put the conseys in there.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And they planned on a tractor.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
They were liked.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
And she would sit on the truck and he'd back up there.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
She put the conseys in.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
Then this would put the fertilizer in the airfoam.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.000
I was your cooking dinner.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
I told you that all the farm you won't dinner right at the time.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
If he was coming out and feeling hungry.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So would you cook for everybody working on the farm?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.000
Oh, yes.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:54.000
Cook for everybody.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
That's a big job.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So I know that you mentioned the cotton and the sawmill.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And the corn, peanuts.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And we had sugar cane.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
All of that brought in money.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
And you also had a store?

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Yeah, we had a grocery store.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Did you and the children ever work in the store?

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
No, he's not running the store.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So she would just take care of it?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
The only thing I did, I felt like the report for the sale tax.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
But still, I felt like the report for them.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
So it's just security for the people who worked at sawmill.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
So you would do some of the paperwork.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.000
When did you first try to register to vote?

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And that's that.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I don't know what year it was.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Then we all got to meet.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
I don't know what year it was.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.000
But I was one of the first to try to register to vote.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And he and Hadisburden.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
So you just mentioned you were one of the first people in the Hadisburden area

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
to try to register to vote?

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
We would go around, feel like, for our application.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Mr. Nene, Nene, never looked at you.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And you would say, I forgot to fill out his hand and turn around.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:12.000
He gave me a card, a 2 by 5 card with the Constitution on part of...

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
some of the Constitution on the card.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:19.000
He told me to read that and tell him what it means.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.000
And of course, I read it and I could very well explain it to him.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
He would tell me, oh, you don't know what you're talking about.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
You didn't pass.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
He never listened.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
When you would go down, would you go by yourself?

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
No, if I don't use you, it would work with me.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
So the two of you would go.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
He would go there, everybody, because he could go down there.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And of course, they took your tag number.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
When you were doing that, is that when they would put your name in the paper for register?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
For trying to register?

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:57.000
What they really would do was send it into your employment.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
But at that time, we'd already made half a day without...

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
to organization we gave money to.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
And ACP was a no-no, you could not give them any money.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
And we had to have that notarized.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
So you would have the deposition notarized?

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:21.000
We'd have to have the form that we feel out of the organization that we gave money to.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
We would have to have that notarized.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
You mean no for the teachers?

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:25.000
For the teachers, yeah.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
Yeah, and then that they would fire you if you...

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
If you gave money to an ACP, we didn't have that nerve to say we gave it to them.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So you wouldn't put that on the form?

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
No, nobody would put it on the form, but we wouldn't do it.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
Were you a member though at that time?

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.000
Oh, yes.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Yeah, you remember.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
So when you go down to register, was Mr. Damon registered at that time?

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
No, he never had a chance to register.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
He never had a chance to vote.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.000
His card came out to be buried him.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
I didn't know that.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.000
No, he never had a chance to vote.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
So all of those years are trying?

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
He never had a chance to vote.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
I always go to the...

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
I never want to vote for absentee.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.000
I never go to the...

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I voted once at the court hour when I had a hip replacement.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
It was on a walker.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
But I always go to the polling place to vote.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
I go to the place they wouldn't let me go.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
Are any of those same people there?

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.000
No.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
But they were when you first started.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
What was that like?

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
Well, by then things had changed.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:39.000
In fact, I worked with someone that was in there.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.000
In his office, I was a election commission and I fought three terms.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Of District 2, I didn't this error.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
Did you run for that office?

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Yes.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
How soon did you run for that office after the vote after Mr. Damon was killed?

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
These are questions I can not ask.

